### LSI
How the Sweep / Pivot Low Logic Works
Pivot detection runs on every 5m bar, all hours, in both engines. A swing low requires:

n_left=8 bars before it with strictly higher lows
n_right=60 bars after it with strictly higher lows
Confirmed only after all 60 right-side bars close — a ~5 hour delay on 5m bars
Once confirmed, the swing low level is forward-filled and persists until a newer swing low replaces it. Swing levels carry across day boundaries — they are never reset.

Sweep detection is gated:

Backtester: in_rth mask (starts at rth_start=09:30)
Execution engine: SCANNING state (starts at entry_start=09:35)
Before that window, sweeps fire from the swing tracker but are ignored by the state machine
What happened on this trade:

A swing low at 24204.50 formed during Sunday night's Asia session (~22:00-23:00 ET April 6)
It was confirmed ~60 bars later (~03:00-04:00 ET April 7)
Pre-market bars from 06:50-09:30 traded well below 24204.50 many times, but those sweeps were outside the entry window — ignored
No new swing low from today has been confirmed yet (n_right=60 means the earliest today's lows could confirm is ~5 hours after they form)
At 09:40 (first SCANNING bar with low < 24204.50), the sweep triggered
Both engines behave identically here. Not a bug — the backtester would produce the same trade on the same data. The stale-looking swept level is a consequence of the large n_right=60 confirmation delay combined with sweep detection being restricted to the entry window.